Here's a Perl script that searches a directory for files containing a given pattern and renames them:

```perl
#!/usr/bin/perl

use strict;
use warnings;

# Set directory path and pattern
my $dir = '/path/to/directory';
my $pattern = 'my_pattern';

# Set new filename prefix
my $new_prefix = 'new_';

# Open directory handle
opendir(my $dh, $dir) or die "Cannot open directory: $!";

# Loop through files in directory
while (my $file = readdir($dh)) {

  # Ignore current and parent directory
  next if ($file =~ /^\.\.?$/);

  # Check if file is a regular file
  next unless (-f "$dir/$file");

  # Open file handle
  open(my $fh, '<', "$dir/$file") or die "Cannot open file: $!";

  # Read file contents into scalar variable
  my $contents = do { local $/; <$fh> };

  # Check if pattern is present in file contents
  if ($contents =~ /$pattern/) {

    # Split filename into prefix and extension
    my ($prefix, $ext) = split('\.', $file);

    # Construct new filename with prefix and new extension
    my $new_filename = "$new_prefix$prefix.$ext";

    # Rename file
    rename("$dir/$file", "$dir/$new_filename") or die "Cannot rename file: $!";

    print "Renamed $file to $new_filename\n";
  }

  # Close file handle
  close($fh);
}

# Close directory handle
closedir($dh);
```

This script takes the directory path and pattern to search for as arguments, as well as a new filename prefix. It then opens the directory, loops through the files, and performs the renaming logic as outlined above. Note that this script modifies the files in place, so be careful when using it!

